---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const schema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@graph': [
    {
      '@type': 'HomeAndConstructionBusiness',
      name: 'Triangle Dehumidifiers, LLC',
      telephone: '(984) 600-3650',
      url: 'https://www.triangledehumidifiers.com',
      areaServed: [
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Raleigh' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Holly Springs' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Cary' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Apex' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Fuquay-Varina' },
      ],
      serviceType: 'Crawlspace Mold Treatment',
    },
    {
      '@type': 'Service',
      name: 'Crawlspace Mold Treatment',
      url: 'https://www.triangledehumidifiers.com/crawlspace-mold-treatment-raleigh',
      telephone: '(984) 600-3650',
      provider: { '@type': 'HomeAndConstructionBusiness', name: 'Triangle Dehumidifiers, LLC' },
      areaServed: [
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Raleigh' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Holly Springs' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Cary' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Apex' },
        { '@type': 'City', name: 'Fuquay-Varina' },
      ],
      description:
        'Crawlspace mold treatment in Raleigh, NC. EPA-registered products. Moisture correction first, then surface treatment.',
    },
  ],
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Crawlspace Mold Treatment Raleigh NC | Triangle Dehumidifiers"
  description="Professional crawlspace mold treatment in Raleigh, NC. EPA-registered products. Moisture correction first, then surface treatment. Serving Wake County and the Triangle region."
  canonical="/crawlspace-mold-treatment-raleigh"
  heroImage="/images/mold-crawlspace-raleigh-nc.webp"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section class="svc-hero">
    <div class="container">
      <h1>Crawlspace Mold Treatment<br />in Raleigh, NC</h1>
      <span class="svc-hero__direct"
        >Mold is a symptom of a moisture problem. We correct the humidity source first — then treat
        existing surface growth to prevent recurrence.</span
      >
      <p class="svc-hero__sub">
        Mold risk increases when crawlspace Relative Humidity (RH) stays above ~65% for extended
        periods. We provide professional crawlspace mold treatment using EPA-registered
        antimicrobial products selected for crawlspace applications.
      </p>
      <div class="svc-hero__actions">
        <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-green">Schedule Crawlspace Mold Inspection</a>
        <a href="tel:9846003650" class="btn btn-secondary">Call (984) 600-3650</a>
      </div>
      <p class="hero-trust-line">EPA-registered products. Licensed &amp; insured.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- MOISTURE FIRST -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="svc-split">
        <div>
          <h2>Moisture Correction Comes First</h2>
          <span class="answer-first"
            >Treating mold without correcting the moisture source is temporary — growth will return
            as long as crawlspace RH remains above ~65% for extended periods.</span
          >
          <p>
            Most crawlspace mold returns because humidity was never corrected. We address both the
            mold and the moisture source — targeting ~50% RH to reduce the conditions that support
            regrowth.
          </p>
          <div class="icon-cards">
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon icon-card__icon--svg">
                <svg
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="1.5"
                  stroke-linecap="round"
                  stroke-linejoin="round"
                >
                  <!-- gauge meter -->
                  <path d="M5.1 19a9 9 0 1 1 13.8 0" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                  <path d="M12 11l-3.5 4" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                  <circle cx="12" cy="15.5" r="1.2" fill="currentColor"></circle>
                  <line x1="7" y1="14" x2="8.2" y2="14.7" stroke-linecap="round"></line>
                  <line x1="17" y1="14" x2="15.8" y2="14.7" stroke-linecap="round"></line>
                  <line x1="12" y1="6" x2="12" y2="7.5" stroke-linecap="round"></line>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <div>
                <strong>Ground Moisture</strong>
                <p>Evaporation through unprotected soil raises crawlspace RH continuously</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon icon-card__icon--svg">
                <svg
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="1.5"
                  stroke-linecap="round"
                  stroke-linejoin="round"
                >
                  <path
                    d="M9.59 4.59A2 2 0 1 1 11 8H2m10.59 11.41A2 2 0 1 0 14 16H2m15.73-8.27A2.5 2.5 0 1 1 19.5 12H2"
                  ></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <div>
                <strong>Humid Exterior Air</strong>
                <p>Open crawlspace vents allow high-humidity air to enter freely</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon icon-card__icon--svg">
                <svg
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="1.5"
                  stroke-linecap="round"
                  stroke-linejoin="round"
                >
                  <!-- pipe with drip -->
                  <rect x="3" y="9" width="18" height="4" rx="2"></rect>
                  <path d="M7 13v2" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                  <path d="M7 15c0 1.5 1.5 2.5 1.5 4" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                  <path d="M12 13v3" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                  <path d="M12 16c0 1.5 1.5 2 1.5 3.5" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <div>
                <strong>Plumbing &amp; Condensation</strong>
                <p>Leaks or condensation on cold pipes add direct moisture to the space</p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="icon-card">
              <span class="icon-card__icon icon-card__icon--svg">
                <svg
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="1.5"
                  stroke-linecap="round"
                  stroke-linejoin="round"
                >
                  <path d="M12 22s8-4 8-10V5l-8-3-8 3v7c0 6 8 10 8 10z"></path>
                  <line x1="4.93" y1="4.93" x2="19.07" y2="19.07"></line>
                </svg>
              </span>
              <div>
                <strong>Missing Vapor Barrier</strong>
                <p>Inadequate vapor barrier coverage dramatically increases moisture load</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc-split__image" style="padding-top:0;">
          <img
            src="/images/mold-crawlspace-raleigh-nc.webp"
            alt="Mold on crawlspace floor joists in Raleigh NC"
            width="780"
            height="320"
            fetchpriority="high"
            style="width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;border-radius:var(--radius-md);display:block;"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- TREATMENT PROCESS -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="svc-split">
        <div>
          <h2>Our Mold Treatment Process</h2>
          <span class="answer-first"
            >After moisture sources are identified, surface mold on crawlspace framing is treated
            with EPA-registered antimicrobial solutions applied directly to affected wood surfaces.</span
          >
          <p>
            We apply treatment by targeted surface cleaning or controlled fogging to reach framing
            areas within the crawlspace.
          </p>
          <div class="svc-steps">
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">1</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Moisture Source Evaluation</h3>
                <p>
                  Identify and document humidity drivers — ground moisture, air entry points,
                  plumbing, and condensation sources.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">2</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Surface Preparation</h3>
                <p>
                  Prepare affected areas for treatment — targeted surface cleaning where practical
                  before product application.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">3</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Antimicrobial Application</h3>
                <p>
                  EPA-registered products applied to affected surfaces using targeted application or
                  controlled fogging as appropriate — no bleach-based approach.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">4</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Post-Treatment Documentation</h3>
                <p>
                  Treated areas photographed and documented — providing a baseline record for future
                  reference.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="svc-step">
              <div class="svc-step__num">5</div>
              <div class="svc-step__body">
                <h3>Humidity Control Plan</h3>
                <p>
                  We recommend a dehumidification and vapor barrier strategy to keep crawlspace RH
                  stable at ~50% and reduce the conditions that support regrowth.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc-split__image" style="padding-top:0;">
          <img
            src="/images/mold-remediation-crawlspace-raleigh-nc.webp"
            alt="Mold remediation in a crawlspace in Raleigh NC"
            width="780"
            height="320"
            loading="lazy"
            style="width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;border-radius:var(--radius-md);display:block;"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- BOTANICAL TREATMENT -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="svc-split">
        <div>
          <h2>EPA-Registered Mold Treatment Products</h2>
          <span class="answer-first"
            >We use EPA-registered antimicrobial products selected for crawlspace applications, with
            application methods designed to minimize disruption.</span
          >
          <p>
            We use EPA-registered products including Benefect Botanical Decon 30 and Concrobium Mold
            Control, both commonly used in professional restoration settings.
          </p>
          <div class="feature-list">
            <div class="feature-item">
              <span class="feature-check">✓</span>
              <span
                >Benefect Botanical Decon 30 — botanical, thymol-based, EPA-registered disinfectant
                used in restoration workflows</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <span class="feature-check">✓</span>
              <span
                >Concrobium Mold Control — EPA-registered; used to inhibit mold growth and leaves a
                residue barrier when applied per label</span
              >
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <span class="feature-check">✓</span>
              <span>No bleach-based shock approach</span>
            </div>
            <div class="feature-item">
              <span class="feature-check">✓</span>
              <span
                >Material-compatible approach for crawlspace wood framing when applied correctly</span
              >
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="svc-split__image" style="padding-top:0;">
          <img
            src="/images/mold-benefect-disinfectant-crawlspace.jpg"
            alt="Benefect botanical disinfectant used for crawlspace mold treatment"
            width="780"
            height="320"
            loading="lazy"
            style="width:100%;height:320px;object-fit:cover;border-radius:var(--radius-md);display:block;"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SCOPE -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>What We Do — and What We Don't Do</h2>
      <span class="answer-first"
        >We provide crawlspace surface treatment and humidity correction. We do not provide mold
        clearance testing or medical advice.</span
      >
      <div class="clarification-box">
        <p><strong>We do not:</strong></p>
        <ul class="clarification-list">
          <li>Perform full structural tear-out remediation</li>
          <li>Treat mold inside living areas</li>
          <li>Clean HVAC duct systems</li>
          <li>Provide mold clearance testing or air quality certification</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <p class="section-top-sm">
        If we observe conditions outside our scope — structural concerns or living-area
        contamination — we document what we see and limit our work to crawlspace moisture control
        and surface treatment within the crawlspace.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- SURFACE MOLD VS ROT -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>Surface Mold vs. Structural Wood Rot</h2>
      <span class="answer-first"
        >Surface mold treated at early stages leaves wood structurally intact — the goal is to halt
        active growth and eliminate the conditions that allowed it to develop.</span
      >
      <p>
        Surface mold — typically appearing as white, gray, or black discoloration on wood framing —
        is different from wood rot, which involves structural degradation of the wood fiber itself.
        Treatment performed before mold penetrates deep into the wood grain typically does not
        compromise structural integrity.
      </p>
      <p>Signs that structural assessment may be needed:</p>
      <div class="signs-grid signs-grid--2col section-top-sm">
        <div class="sign-card">
          <div class="sign-card__icon">
            <svg
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              fill="none"
              stroke="var(--color-primary)"
              stroke-width="1.5"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              stroke-linejoin="round"
              ><path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"></path><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5"></path><path
                d="M2 12l10 5 10-5"></path></svg
            >
          </div>
          <p>Soft, spongy, or crumbling wood when pressed</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-card">
          <div class="sign-card__icon">
            <svg
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              fill="none"
              stroke="var(--color-primary)"
              stroke-width="1.5"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              stroke-linejoin="round"
              ><path
                d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"
              ></path><line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"></line><line
                x1="12"
                y1="17"
                x2="12.01"
                y2="17"></line></svg
            >
          </div>
          <p>Fungal growth with a shelf-like or 3D structure</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-card">
          <div class="sign-card__icon">
            <svg
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              fill="none"
              stroke="var(--color-primary)"
              stroke-width="1.5"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              stroke-linejoin="round"
              ><path d="M3 9l9-7 9 7v11a2 2 0 0 1-2 2H5a2 2 0 0 1-2-2z"></path><polyline
                points="9 22 9 12 15 12 15 22"></polyline></svg
            >
          </div>
          <p>Sagging floors above the crawlspace</p>
        </div>
        <div class="sign-card">
          <div class="sign-card__icon">
            <svg
              xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
              viewBox="0 0 24 24"
              fill="none"
              stroke="var(--color-primary)"
              stroke-width="1.5"
              stroke-linecap="round"
              stroke-linejoin="round"><path d="M13 2L3 14h9l-1 8 10-12h-9l1-8z"></path></svg
            >
          </div>
          <p>Visible separation or cracking along the wood grain</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- PREVENTION -->
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container narrow">
      <h2>Mold Prevention Requires Both Treatment + Humidity Control</h2>
      <span class="answer-first"
        >The most effective long-term approach is treating existing growth and controlling humidity
        so it doesn't return.</span
      >
      <p>
        Crawlspace mold is rarely solved by treatment alone, and humidity control alone doesn't
        remove existing growth. We combine surface treatment with a humidity control plan designed
        to keep crawlspace RH stable — typically 45–50% RH after corrective work — reducing the
        conditions that support regrowth.
      </p>
      <p>
        For vented crawlspaces see our <a href="/crawlspace-dehumidifier-installation-raleigh"
          >professional crawlspace dehumidifier installation in Raleigh</a
        >. For sealed systems see our <a href="/encapsulated-crawlspace-dehumidifier-raleigh-nc"
          >encapsulated crawlspace dehumidifier installation</a
        > page.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- BOTTOM CTA -->
  <section class="svc-cta">
    <div class="container svc-cta__inner">
      <h2>Stop Crawlspace Mold at the Source — Not Just the Surface</h2>
      <p>
        Serving Raleigh and Wake County, including Cary, Apex, Holly Springs, and Fuquay-Varina.
      </p>
      <a href="/contact" class="btn btn-green">Schedule Crawlspace Mold Inspection</a>
      <span class="svc-cta__trust">EPA-registered botanical products available.</span>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
